Introduction

Were going to do some basic analysis on NFL teams from 2002-2020. This consists of the 16-game-per-season era.

Lets import some important libraries.

First, we will conduct some exploration and try to understand the dataset first. Then, we will explore the relationship of points. Well explore points scored, points allowed, and point differential versus wins. Obviously, for individual games, measurements like point differential are highly correlated with wins, but over the average course of a season we might see different results.

Note: After the analysis, it makes more sense to plot pct instead (I think it takes into account draws as well). Overall the graphs should still look the same.

Finally, I would like to conduct a search for outliers of these statistics. For example, which team is the most clutch, that is, has the highest win rate with a low point differential. We could see the clutchest team in a season or the clutchest overall NFL team throughout the 16-game era. Alternatively, we could also explore the least clutch team, the chokers.

There are honestly a lot of columns. For now, lets filter our data. What columns should we keep? season, team, wins, losses, ties, pct, scored, allowed, and net all make sense. Lets also keep seed, it might come in handy later.

df <- select(df, c(season, team, wins, losses, ties, pct, scored, allowed, net, seed))

There are 32 teams in the NFL, and 19 years in this dataset. Lets create an aggregated dataset where we combine all of a teams stats.

combined_df <- df %>%
  group_by(team) %>%
  summarise(wins = sum(wins), losses = sum(losses), ties = sum(ties),
            pct = mean(pct), scored = sum(scored), allowed = sum(allowed),
            net = sum(net), seed = mean(seed))
print(combined_df)

Alright, now its time to do some very basic plotting. Lets just look at scored vs pct in the original data.

ggplot(data=df, aes(x = scored, y = pct)) + geom_point()

Very interesting. For the most part, of course we see a direct positive correlation. The more you score, the more you win, right? But what about the line on the left, which essentially has a bunch of super low scoring team. My hypothesis is that some of our data is missing, so lets go ahead and split by year.

ggplot(data=df, aes(x = scored, y = pct, color=factor(season))) + geom_point()

Okay, the colors are confusing, but I think we can clearly tell that theres something wrong with the data from 2020 or so. Lets plot the filtered data from 2016 onwards.

df_2016_plus <- subset(df, df$season >= 2016)
ggplot(data=df_2016_plus, aes(x = scored, y = pct, color=factor(season))) + geom_point()

Now its very clear that we only have problems with 2020. Lets inspect the data.

Its clear that our data is a bit outdated and doesnt have everything in the 2020 season. Lets update our dataset to only include analysis from 2002-2019 for the graphs. Lets update the combined dataset as well. (as means may be lopsided by overweighting 2020).

df <- subset(df, df$season < 2020)
combined_df <- df %>%
  group_by(team) %>%
  summarise(wins = sum(wins), losses = sum(losses), ties = sum(ties),
            pct = mean(pct), scored = sum(scored), allowed = sum(allowed),
            net = sum(net), seed = mean(seed))

Now lets go ahead and plot scored, allowed, and net vs pct for our data.

ggplot(data=df, aes(x=scored, y=pct)) + geom_point(color=factor(df$season)) + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data=df, aes(x=allowed, y=pct)) + geom_point(color=factor(df$season)) + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data=df, aes(x=net, y=pct)) + geom_point(color=factor(df$season)) + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Honestly, just as expected. There is a strong correlation between scored points, allowed points, and an extremely strong correlation for net points. Lets calculate the correlation exactly.

print(cor(x=df$scored, y=df$pct))
## [1] 0.7430125
print(cor(x=df$allowed, y=df$pct))
## [1] -0.6783799
print(cor(x=df$net, y=df$pct))
## [1] 0.915151

Interestingly enough, defense is not as correlated. Theres too many dots on these graphs, and labeling would be a visual nightmare. Lets switch over to the combined datasets. Lets look at the generic plots before answering/asking any questions.

ggplot(data=combined_df, aes(x=scored, y=pct)) + geom_point() + geom_text(aes(label=combined_df$team))
## Warning: Use of `combined_df$team` is discouraged. Use `team` instead.
